flowRoot.flowPara: Python is an easy to learn programming language. Its clear syntax and high level data structures make it an ideal first language. The availability of libraries for tasks like graphics, networking, scientific computation makes it a very simple and valuable tool for problem solving. The Python interpreter is freely downloadable and available on almost all popular operating systems.

Proprietary software offers restricted functionality for an often unfair price. There is a better alternative: The free software movement, started in 1983 by Richard M. Stallman, when he launched a project called GNU (www.gnu.org), which along with the Linux kernel formed the GNU/Linux operating system. A large number of software packages are freely available for multimedia, office tasks, coding, image editing, scientific computation etc. There are several GNU/Linux distributions you can choose from. Ubuntu is one such user friendly flavour.
Python as a Tool for Computer Aided Education

The decision by CBSE to introduce Python at the higher secondary level opens up the possibilities of using it as a tool for teaching science and mathematics. Plotting the graphs of different algebraic and trigonometric functions helps to understand them better. Problems in physics can also be explored using simple Python programs. Some examples like the trajectory of a charged particle in electric and magnetic fields, electric field around point charges etc., are shown on the left. More resources are available at www.expeyes.in
